tional: originally a byname from a vocabulary word meaning ‘eminent, conspicuous’; it was common in the Middle Ages and was revived in the 20th-century."]},{"name":"Howell","meanings":["Anglicized form of the Welsh name Hywel , or a transferred use of the surname derived from that name."]}]},{"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the names beginning with this syllable."],"variants":[{"name":"Alexander","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]},{"name":"Ieuaf","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Latin <i>Iohannes</i>.  See  <b>John</b>   ."],"variants":[{"name":"Iefan","meanings":["Later form of   Ieuan ."]},{"name":"Ifan","meanings":["From Latin <i>Iohannes</i>.  See  <b>John</b>   ."]},{"name":"John","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."]}]},{"name":"Goch","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Italian <b>Rocco</b>; ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Hywel ap Ieuaf Goch was born about 1225, in Gwern-y-go, Montgomeryshire, Wales, United Kingdom, his father, Ieuaf Goch ap Griffith Carno, was 27 and his mother, Mrs. Ieuaf of Montgomery, was 23. He had at least 1 son with Hywel ap Leuaf."},"et":{"Abt 1225–":"umbes 1225–Surnud","1225–Male":"1225–Surnud","1228–Male":"1228–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1255–Male":"1255–Surnud","1200–Male":"1200–Surnud","1204–Female":"1204–Surnud","1228":"1228","1204":"1204","1225":"1225","Abt 1255":"umbes 1255","1200":"1200","1255":"1255","Abt 1225":"umbes 1225","Gwern-y-go, LlnfhnglyNghr, Montgomery, Wales":"Gwern-y-go, Montgomeryshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Elstn Gldrdd":"Elston, Chegutu, Mashonaland West, Zimbabwe","Montgomery, Wales":"Montgomeryshire, Wales"},"fi":{"Abt 1225–":"noin 1225–Kuollut","1225–Male":"1225–Kuollut","1228–Male":"1228–Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1255–Male":"1255–Kuollut","1200–Male":"1200–Kuollut","1204–Female":"1204–Kuollut","1228":"1228","1204":"1204","1225":"1225","Abt 1255":"noin 12